Introduction
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 3
Introduction
The Adventure of Turbulence
The 16 personality types are each defined by a unique combination of four traits.
In your case, the Introverted, Observant, Feeling, and Prospecting traits form the
special recipe for the Adventurer (ISFP) personality type. Congratulations! There’s
also a fifth trait, called Identity, that defines every individual as either Assertive or
Turbulent. That little difference on paper can spell out big differences in life.
Whether you’ve fully understood them or not, you’re living the effects of the
Turbulent trait every day.
Some troublesome thoughts and behaviors that are more likely for Turbulent
personalities include:
● anxiety about future events,
● unreasonable self-criticism,
● pessimistic reactions to challenges, and
● fear of social rejection.
Does that sound ominous (or familiar)? Don’t worry. The word turbulent isn’t
always used positively, but there’s nothing wrong with your personality. We call it
the Turbulent trait because that accurately describes a dynamic way of being, with
a tendency toward rapid shifts and strong reactions. While the Turbulent trait may
bring certain challenges, your personality also grants you wonderful benefits.
Any dynamic activity is a source of energy (like a river powering a waterwheel),
and living your Turbulent personality positively just requires understanding it.
Turbulence can create optimism, joy, and enthusiasm – it provides you with inner
Introduction
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 4
drive and motivation. In fact, when mixed with your other personality traits, one
might even call some aspects of your Turbulent personality superpowers.
How Will This Book Help You?
What’s the most important thing in life? You probably have your own answer to
that question, but our goal here is to help you work toward self-awareness.
Understanding yourself is a lifelong practice that makes all other goals, like
wealth, security, happiness, and rewarding relationships, easier to achieve. Being
your best self doesn’t mean being perfect – it means living by your strengths and
finding your own ways to make the best of any situation.
Negative feelings and challenges are inevitable in life, and expecting otherwise will
likely result in disappointment. Living a happy and fulfilling life doesn’t guarantee
that things will always be smooth, and sometimes the right way is a Turbulent
one. (Wink.) At least one of the most important things in life is understanding
yourself – and what you’re capable of.
So we want to put the power in your hands by helping you explore the way that
you are. Gaining insight into your personality helps you develop behaviors and
habits that feel right to you. Here, we’ll focus on the Turbulent side of your
personality and how it affects your life in several important areas. We’ll also offer
some examples of mindsets and methods that tend to work well for Turbulent
Adventurers.
You don’t need to change who you are to grow as a person. Chances are you’re
already doing many things that bring you happiness and success – you’re flexing
your Turbulent Adventurer superpowers. But it’s important to consciously
recognize what is and isn’t working for you. Let’s explore more of what it means
to be a Turbulent Adventurer and where your personality might take you.
The Social World
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 5
The Social World
Socializing
We humans are social creatures (for better or worse). As an Introverted
personality type, you may not crave a huge amount of social contact, but
socializing can still have a powerful effect on your happiness. Friendship can be
essential for Turbulent Adventurers – good friends provide amazing support and
soul-sustaining joy and laughter.
Sometimes all it takes to feel accepted is just one or two good people. Big groups
and busy social schedules can be fun, but they can also result in a scattered
experience. For your personality type, diving into the social realm on a grand scale
is optional – dabbling and experimenting around the edges can be satisfying
enough. Random people can come into your life in unexpected ways, and you may
find that you welcome such experiences with happy surprise.
Your Turbulent trait indicates that how other people react to you strongly affects
how you see yourself. When you feel like you belong and are appreciated, it’s
deeply satisfying. You may notice that your social style changes depending on who
you’re with, naturally meshing with their manner and mindset. You might be more
talkative, more serious, joke more, or be bolder about embracing experiences.
Each person you meet is not only a potential friend but also a chance to
experience yourself in a new light. That’s an adventure in itself and a good reason
to be sociable. However, when you don’t get along with someone, Turbulence can
inflate your negative reactions, making you feel like there’s something wrong with
you.
A common problem for Turbulent Adventurers like you occurs when the desire to
avoid those negative feelings makes your social decisions for you. Thoughts like,
The Social World
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 6
What if they don’t like me? can make you reluctant to enter social situations, even
in the company of friends. Furthermore, worrying about what your friends might
think of you can make it harder to be honest or comfortable with them.
Everyone has their own level of social inclination – the right amount brings
fulfillment, and too much or too little does not. You tend to be at your happiest
when you let those core inclinations and limits guide you rather than any worries.
You may indeed be sensitive to social feedback, but that isn’t a bad thing when
you’re honoring your own needs. You have a remarkable ability to immerse
yourself in an experience by absorbing where you are and what’s going on.
Distancing yourself from your mind’s worries takes conscious effort, but that’s
how you access the positive feedback in your environment – which is kind of the
point of socializing. Whether you’re out with a group or just hanging out at home
with a friend, connecting with something outside yourself is rewarding. Stepping
into the flow of what’s around you is a classic way to discover social happiness as
a Turbulent Adventurer.
Romance
The most exciting social connection might be a romantic one. Seeking romance
can feel a bit like diving for treasure, with currents pushing you around and a lot
of risks and distractions to navigate. And, yes, you might investigate a lot of wrecks
before you find a gem worth holding on to. For Turbulent Adventurers, the
emotional stakes can feel much higher in romance than in friendship, but love has
a way of pulling people together past doubts and confusion.
Your own warmth and empathy tend to draw compatible people to you, even if
you’re not a very gregarious person. The key to positive romantic connections is
often overcoming your own fear of risk, but even that can go too far. Turbulent

“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 7
Adventurers sometimes become beguiled by hopes that blind them to reality. Yet
your path to romantic happiness is the same one that leads you past worry: being
mindful of what’s going on in the moment and your reactions to it.
Trying to guess where a potential romance is headed can be distracting and may
even interfere with blossoming happiness between two people. You’re fortunate,
though. While Turbulent Adventurers crave assurances of love and trust as much
as anyone, they don’t always need much structure in their relationships beyond
that emotional feedback. For people with your personality type, romance is more
about feelings than labels.
Making your own rules to meet your needs can be very freeing. Of course, the
best relationships require that you listen to your partner’s needs as well. As a
Turbulent Adventurer, you likely offer your partner a vast degree of acceptance,
and you aren’t wrong to expect the same in return. Yet different personalities have
their own ideas and ideals about relationships. One of your best assets in a
romantic relationship is your ability to be flexible in how you pursue your goals.
Two people can have the same objective of a loving, fulfilling relationship in mind
yet see very different routes toward that goal. They may even have different needs
within the relationship. You have a wonderful ability to accommodate what works
for both you and your partner. Turbulent Adventurer tolerance can seem like a
magical superpower to more rigid personality types.
That flexible mindset also helps ensure that your needs are met, because the
example that you set can shape your relationship. It’s very important to ask for
what you need and to let your partner reciprocate your efforts to accommodate
them. Your Turbulence can create great emotional need, and your partner can’t
serve that need unless you make them aware of how you feel and what they can
do to make you happy.

Happiness also requires honesty with yourself, and the truth is that some
romances fade. (Ouch!) Remember that treasure-diving analogy? Well, Turbulent
Adventurers are known for their spontaneous enthusiasm, and sometimes you
just can’t help falling for the newest shiny thing. When the novelty wears off, you
may find that it doesn’t look so shiny after all.
Infatuation can lead you into difficult situations, but being self-aware can help
keep you out of trouble. And, no, that doesn’t mean suppressing your enthusiasm
for a new romance – that excitement is one of the best feelings. But understanding
your own personality lets you see objectively what’s happening as you make
choices. You can go where the currents take you, but you’ll also be able to hear
your own warning bell when you’re being swept toward danger.
Going with the Flow
Your natural sense of curiosity is stronger than that of many personality types,
and that’s partly driven by your Turbulence. Social restlessness can be a good
thing when you open yourself to new experiences. What’s next? What’s over
there? Is it fun? For Turbulent Adventurers like you, making positive connections
doesn’t mean limiting yourself to just a few. It’s in your personality traits to want
to jump around and experiment with seeking fulfillment in different ways.
Of course, not everything will be fun for you. Finding social happiness requires
some degree of conscious balance. It means staying open to experiences without
feeling obligated to participate in those that you don’t like or avoiding
opportunities due to worry. Joyful human connections can be found in unlikely
places, if you’re willing to seek them.
You could say that going with the flow is a Turbulent Adventurer superpower. You
can allow social experiences to happen in an organic way, seeking positive feelings

“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 9
and rewarding relationships wherever they naturally happen. Some personalities
exhaust a lot of energy trying to control everything, only to discover that they
can’t. People with your personality type are known for being adaptable, and you
can find happiness by being mindful of your circumstances more than trying to
manipulate them.
Part of that is knowing when to seek a new direction when something isn’t working
for you. Letting go can be harder for Turbulent personalities, because your
emotions can feel like quite a storm. But the immense return of energy that you
receive from practicing self-awareness and self-acceptance helps you endure
difficult changes. Not getting stuck where you don’t want to be is a critical part of
finding happiness in the social world.

Dear Diary,
Is it selfish to do what I want? I’ve been paying more attention to my own
feelings. Worrying about what people think of me makes it kind of hard
to relax and have fun. It’s not like I’m going around being rude or
anything – I still want to get along. It’s just that I don’t want my social life
to depend on doing what’s expected of me or what makes me look good,
instead of what I actually enjoy.
People seem to do and think whatever they want no matter what I do, so
I’m just doing what I want. It’s so freeing not to feel trapped, and because
of that, it’s actually less stressful. I can just go along with the flow and
stay in the moment, instead of getting all caught up in what might
happen.
Actually, that’s kind of revolutionized my dating too. Don’t get me wrong,
it’s still rough when something doesn’t work, but I’ve realized that it’s
pointless to waste energy on things that I can’t change. I just let my true
feelings come up without judging them, but I try not to hold on to
negativity. I can’t let that stand in the way of meeting the right person.
I’ve been going on more dates and trying to keep my head in the moment
by paying attention to how someone makes me feel. I don’t mean to be
picky, and I hate the idea of hurting anyone’s feelings, but without that
spark, it’s just not worth it. What’s weird is that sometimes the people I
should find the most attractive leave me cold, and some people I
normally wouldn’t look twice at turn out to be a lot of fun.

I just want to feel free to be myself, more than anything else. People who

Achievement
Confidence and Motivation
For a personality type that often benefits from going with the flow, some parts of
life can feel like they have hard edges. The everyday world makes certain demands
of you, such as job performance, schoolwork, or other important life goals. For
Turbulent Adventurers like you, it’s not always easy to maintain your confidence
and motivation, but it’s all too easy to worry about your performance.
But one great thing about being a personality type that loves excitement and
novelty is that you can find those things almost anywhere, with the right attitude.
You probably can’t help but look for the unusual or fun side of things, even in
situations that most people would see as serious. That can make mundane
circumstances more exciting and give you energy to achieve your goals. Being
open to the flow of positive energy is one of your Turbulent Adventurer
superpowers.
Perhaps the most important kind of positive energy comes when you fully
appreciate your own successes, no matter how small. You build your confidence
by seeing yourself as capable, and the proof lies in anything that you’ve
accomplished. That kind of positive self-awareness flies in the face of self-doubt.
It’s natural that as a Turbulent personality, you’ll sometimes swing between
positive and negative states. Taking full advantage of the upswing is one way that
you succeed in life.
That idea matches your own fun-seeking nature as well. It’s not pleasant to focus
on failure, so you learn what you can, move forward, and do better. Your carefree
side can help you let go of self-criticism to free up energy and make room for
Achievement
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 13
hope. That’s a productive approach that gets better for you the more you practice
it.
Focus and Finishing
Most Turbulent Adventurers don’t feel like they have adequate focus, and you
probably know what that’s like. You sometimes get distracted from your goals,
lose interest, or have a hard time finishing what you start. But have you ever
considered why that might be? You can leap into something when you’re excited
to do it, so why are some things harder to accomplish than others?
One simple answer is reward: when something isn’t rewarding, your energy and
attention falter. That’s part of being a Turbulent Adventurer, and it doesn’t stop
you from reaching goals. Your way of accomplishing things doesn’t look like
everyone else’s, and that might lead you to question yourself – or lead other
people to question you. But people with your personality type are capable of
achieving stunningly successful results in ways that work for them.
When it comes to major but mundane obligations, whatever ultimate reward
you’re striving for can motivate you, even if it’s not a joyful one. (For example,
keeping your bills paid.) Pragmatism might not seem like a superpower, but it’s a
crucial asset that often gives you a boost. Self-criticism over your ability to focus
may stem from a deeper fear that you lack willpower or ability. Necessity is a great
teacher because it shows you what you’re capable of doing when you have to do
it – it proves your willpower and ability.
Excitement can offer a similar lesson, making your energy surge enough to
overcome huge obstacles. When you’re gripped with desire, your energy naturally
flows toward whatever’s important to you at any given time. You have little trouble
focusing on the things that you’re truly enthusiastic about, so any question about
Achievement
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 14
your focus is quite possibly a question of desire. When you really want something,
you have excellent abilities at your disposal and the willpower to apply them.
Finding a Good Flow
One of the ways that Turbulent Adventurers achieve important goals is by
embracing their shifts in focus, so that their energy is directed where it can
accomplish the most. Instead of sticking to one task or course of action when it
becomes truly unfulfilling, they set it aside and focus on another priority until it
becomes important again. Working on multiple goals back and forth may not
always be efficient, but it can keep you productively engaged. More importantly,
it can keep you happy.
Not every priority in life allows for such multitasking, and some things simply must
be done. However, there’s a part of you that wants to ask the question, If this is so
unfulfilling, why am I doing it? The answer might be necessity or it might be based
on an assumption or habit. If that’s the case, you may have more options than you
think, and exploring options is a big part of what makes Turbulent Adventurers
happy.
Life can carry you along like a river, bringing you into experiences that are a matter
of course. If you find yourself in circumstances that don’t work for you, you might
need to find a better flow to be in. Changes like a new job, new relationship, or
new place to live can be transformative, if not always easy. As a Turbulent
Adventurer, you have a natural desire to experience new possibilities. When you
make a needed change, it may feel like life has taken on a whole new course.
It takes some conscious skill to recognize what you need and what’s standing in
the way of your happiness. As a Turbulent Adventurer, you’re not likely to try to
force your environment to match a specific vision. Instead, you often adapt to your
Achievement
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 15
environment, allowing positive things to flow forth in a natural way. That approach
can work very well, but it requires being where good things will come. Being willing
to find that flow is a Turbulent Adventurer superpower.

Dear Diary,
I feel like a failure when I don’t do the dishes. Don’t judge me (you’re my
diary, after all!), but it’s like a metaphor for my life. Yes, I know they need
to be done – I like clean dishes, but I just have a hard time making myself
do them. I’ve got so much stuff that I want to do that sometimes it’s hard
to get anything done.
Does that matter, though? I mean, I handle my important priorities when
I have to. I’ve learned that when I really want something, I can make it
happen, even if I have to pick myself up when I stumble. When I feel
overwhelmed by a challenge, I try to keep in mind all those times when
things seemed hopeless but I managed to proceed anyway. Sometimes it
just takes putting one foot in front of the other.
When it comes to my personal goals, though, I don’t like getting too
caught up in deadlines. The whole point is to get what I want out of life,
and honestly, what I want can change. What was important yesterday
might take a back seat today. I don’t see any point in forcing myself to
keep doing something arbitrarily. If it’s important, I’ll finish it later, and if
I don’t, then it doesn’t matter as much as I thought. What’s wrong with
that?
I suppose the dishes are kind of similar – if I want a clean plate badly
enough, I’ll wash it. Or maybe it’s time to get a dishwasher and focus on
things that are more important to me than doing dishes.

Embracing Happiness
Attitude Changes
Finding a positive flow to be in is one of the ways that Turbulent Adventurers stay
happy, but the external world is only part of what affects your happiness. It’s
possible to sabotage the best circumstances, opportunities, and experiences with
negative self-talk. As a Turbulent Adventurer, you’ve had moments in life where
your inner feelings made it hard to enjoy anything – or to believe that anything
good could happen.
But then something comes along to distract you from those feelings and rekindle
your inspiration and enthusiasm. Your inner state has a powerful effect on your
life, but your negativity can be fickle. Let it be! Your tendency as a Turbulent
Adventurer toward rapid shifts in attitude can be a superpower when it helps
change a dark mindset into something brighter. Thanks to your openness and
love of novelty, such shifts are easier for you to make than they are for many
personality types.
The personality traits that might cause you trouble in some areas of life also help
you shake off sadness, doubt, and worry, and it all starts with shifting your
attention. Sometimes that’s triggered by other people presenting opportunities
for fun and adventure, while other times a personal task or project will absorb
your mind. Either way, being able to accept a spontaneous change to a more
positive mindset is one of the remarkable ways that Turbulent Adventurers find
happiness.
Embracing Happiness
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 18
Being Alone
Turbulent Adventurers like you often explore a variety of ways of seeking
happiness. The social world is full of opportunities for fulfillment, but some of the
most important time that you can spend is with yourself. The positive rewards
that you receive for following your own inspiration are very special, because
they’re entirely self-created. Solitude can be a private little world where you are
the source of your own happiness.
What that looks like is highly individual. For some Turbulent Adventurers, it could
mean hiking in nature, while for others, it could be making art, crafting, or just
feeding your mind with a good book. It doesn’t matter much what you’re doing
when doing it brings you joy. Consciously acknowledging the positive feedback
that you receive from joyful endeavors (solitary or otherwise) motivates you to
keep reaching for the things that make you happy – as well as new inspirations.
But there’s something more: being happier in life also means allowing yourself to
be sad at times, without guilt or judgment. Often, the best way to sustain your
overall happiness is by taking the time that you need to process your feelings and
heal in your own mind. The power of being alone is that it grants you the ability
to connect with yourself and explore what you find there.
Being aware of your own needs is a superpower. That means being wise about
when you’ll benefit from engaging with the world outside yourself and when you
need to focus on your inner self, by yourself. Some people may not understand
your need for personal time, but ensuring that you prioritize it anyway is one of
the most important ways that you support your happiness.
Embracing Happiness

Being in the Moment
As a Turbulent Adventurer, you often struggle with worries about how the future
might unfold. One of the best things about being open to the flow of events in
your life is that it can foster an attitude of acceptance more than anxiety. There’s
a core logic in the way that Turbulent Adventurers like you don’t usually operate
with detailed planning, because the unknown can’t always be planned for. Not
every personality type can handle that, but you tend to do better than many with
the unknown, despite your worries.
You’re at your best when you just deal with what happens, when it happens. That’s
brilliant in many ways. You don’t waste as much time and energy being upset or
miss valuable experiences because you’re distracted by the future. Staying
present in the moment is one of the greatest Turbulent Adventurer superpowers
by far. But that doesn’t mean that you surrender to predestination or that you’re
powerless, just that you wait until a challenge is revealed before tackling it.
Another benefit of allowing experiences to flow from the unknown without
worrying is that most things aren’t as bad as your doubt would have you believe.
Staying in the moment means that your perceptions reflect what’s actually
happening in your life, instead of pessimistic imaginings. In other words, you’re
living in truth instead of fear. That not only gives you better information with
which to make choices but also makes it a lot easier to be happy.

Dear Diary,
It’s been a long journey, but learning to understand and accept myself
feels like such a weight off my shoulders. I spent so many years feeling
inadequate and trying to be someone else in order to be “happy.” But you
know what? I am what I am, and it doesn’t get any better than that. I’m
still working on being the best version of myself, but I don’t feel like there’s
anything wrong with me. I’m not perfect, and I’m only human, just like
everyone else.
Perfection isn’t possible, but it’s hard to see that in other people because
we don’t know them like we know ourselves. We see our own flaws as so
big compared to other people’s, but everybody struggles with something.
I’m not ashamed of that anymore. I’m okay with myself, including all my
thoughts and feelings. I might have a few rough spots and dark corners,
but they don’t define me.
Aaaaah! Sometimes I wish that things would just be easy all the time, but
I guess that’s unrealistic. The more I practice letting go of all the stuff that
doesn’t make me happy or move me forward, the easier life gets.
Challenges will always come up, I think, either from outside or inside
myself, but I’ll just work through them, like I always do. There’s really no
other choice. Most of my life is going pretty great, and I want to stay in
that flow, as much as humanly possible.
Conclusion: Loving the Turbulent Adventurer You Are
“Turbulent Adventurer Superpowers” (ISFP-T) 21
Conclusion: Loving the Turbulent
Adventurer You Are
The unknown is full of infinite possibilities, and your Turbulence can make that
seem a bit scary at times. But as a Turbulent Adventurer, your natural inclinations
are on your side, including your curiosity to experience new things and a desire
for rewarding emotional connections. That’s a fantastic recipe for a happy, fulfilled
life.
It’s true that your Turbulent personality can make for some swings along the way,
but while it sometimes seems to hold you back, it will ultimately pull you forward.
Dynamic energy can work in your favor, because your Turbulent trait is controlled
by your own intent and awareness. It’s possible to make it flow in your favor if you
try – at least, most of the time.
And the rest of the time, you can try not to take things too seriously (also a
Turbulent Adventurer superpower!). Understanding your personality with love
and acceptance is the best way to handle its difficult aspects. When you’re kind to
and patient with yourself, you’ll find the flow that you need to be in, and it will take
you to wonderful places. Life might be a Turbulent adventure, but your
personality means you’re perfectly suited to it.
As a little reminder of how awesome you are, here are some positive qualities
associated with your personality type, the Turbulent Adventurer:
● Peaceable: Turbulent Adventurers are among the personalities least likely
to meet aggression with aggression.
● Compassionate: You’re one of the most sympathetic and empathetic
personalities.
